Install Apache Server on an EC2 Instance
Steps:
Update the package repository

bash
sudo apt update
Install Apache

bash
sudo apt install apache2 -y
Enable Apache to start on boot

bash
sudo systemctl enable apache2
Start Apache service

bashExtract the ZIP file

bash
unzip your-website.zip
Copy extracted files to Apache’s root directory

bash
sudo cp -r your-website/* /var/www/html/
Set correct permissions

bash
sudo chown -R www-data:www-data /var/www/html/
sudo chmod -R 755 /var/www/html/
sudo systemctl start apache2
Check Apache status

bash
sudo systemctl status apache2
Verify installation
Open a browser and go to your EC2 public IP:
http://<your-ec2-public-ip>



Download your website files (ZIP)

bash
wget http://example.com/your-website.zip
Install unzip (if not already installed)

bash
sudo apt install unzip -y

Extract the ZIP file

bash
unzip your-website.zip
Copy extracted files to Apache’s root directory

bash
sudo cp -r your-website/* /var/www/html/
Set correct permissions

bash
sudo chown -R www-data:www-data /var/www/html/
sudo chmod -R 755 /var/www/html/

Allow HTTP/HTTPS traffic in EC2 Security Group

Go to AWS EC2 console → Security Groups → Inbound rules

Add rules for:

HTTP (port 80)

HTTPS (port 443)


